<br>
Personally, I think that RF is doing OK by responding as much as they did and moving on.  Depending on the story you believe, RF possibly violated *Rathe Convention*.  By both stories, SoT violated *EverQuest Rules*.  Which do you think GMs care about?<br>
<br>
I think both groups should just move on, making whatever adjustments to their alliance as they see fit.  SoT declaring &quot;war&quot; on RF is their second call of poor judgement in this situation and it has publicly opened the door for GM scrutiny of SoT.  I predict that the first time that SoT ganks an RF spawn because of this declared &quot;war&quot;, they will be disbanded.  Anyone with sense sees this declaration of &quot;war&quot; on RF as having little, if not zero, substance.  Perhaps it is venting some anger and making SoT feel better but it cannot, and will not, have any real effect in the game other than that.<br>
<br>
I do not know what really happened in PoG, nor do I really care.  I'm not making a judgement call one way or another saying who was the &quot;most wrong&quot;.  However the facts that both sides agree upon show that SoT violated the Rules of Conduct of Everquest and I know how that works with the GMs, so that is clear.  Whether or not RF ganked SoT's tree or whether it was legitimately theirs, who can say.  I can't because I was not there and will probably never know the true story.  Ganking spawns is pretty low, in my opinion, but I don't have enough information to know if that is what happened.  Regardless of what percipitated SoT's actions, SoT's actions were the results of poor judgement, perhaps caused by heat of passion.  Regardless, the actions are clear.<br>
<br>
It is unfortunate that something like this happened but it did.  You can't erase time but you can adjust and deal with the future.  I suggest to both (all) sides to do that and move on from here.<br>
